child rearing to criminal justice, and are transforming the ways we "know ourselves" as human beings. In this emerging neuro-ontology, we are not "determined" by our neurobiology: on the contrary, it appears that we can and should seek to improve ourselves by understanding and acting on our brains. Neuro examines the implications of this emerging trend, weighing the promises against the perils, and evaluating some widely held concerns about a neurobiological "colonization" of the social and human sciences. Despite identifying many exaggerated claims and premature promises, Neuro argues that the openness provided by the new styles of thought taking shape in neuroscience, with its contemporary conceptions of the neuromolecular, plastic, and social brain, could make possible a new and productive engagement between the social and brain sciences. Copyright note: Reproduction, including downloading of Joan Miro works is prohibited by copyright laws and international conventions without the express written permission of Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York. ?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNeuropsychology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aamygdala.  aanimal experiments.  aanimal models.  aartificiality.  abehavioral research.  abiological processes.  abrain activation.  abrain function.  abrain imaging data.  abrain imaging.  abrain science.  abrain size.  abrain structure.  aclinical medicine.  acognition.  acriminal conduct.  acriminal justice system.  aemotion.  aenvironmental influences.  aevolution.  afunctional brain imaging.  agene expression.  agenomics.  ahuman antisocial behavior.  ahuman behavior.  ahuman brain.  ahuman cognition.  ahuman sciences.  amental illness.  amental life.  amental processes.  amental states.  amolecules